15. Domain Controller Recovery and Validation
Objective
Validate that Disaster Recovery Domain Controllers are operational and capable of supporting authentication, DNS resolution, Group Policy processing, and Active Directory communications before any dependent workload recovery begins.
Domain Controllers represent the foundational service upon which the remainder of the environment depends.
No database, application, web server, or user validation should proceed until Domain Controller functionality has been confirmed.
 
⸻
 
Background
The Disaster Recovery environment utilizes the same Active Directory domain as Production.
Example:
corp.company.com
The Domain Controllers recovered into DR are responsible for:
	•	User Authentication
	•	Computer Authentication
	•	Group Policy Processing
	•	DNS Services
	•	LDAP Queries
	•	Kerberos Authentication
	•	Domain Join Operations
Failure of these services typically causes downstream failures across all application tiers.
 
⸻
 
Dependencies
Before beginning Domain Controller validation, confirm:
	•	DR Readiness Validation completed
	•	AWS Console access available
	•	Systems Manager operational
	•	Required security groups available
	•	Required subnets available
 
⸻
 
Validation Areas
Active Directory Services
Validate:
	•	Domain Controller online
	•	Active Directory services running
	•	SYSVOL accessible
	•	NETLOGON accessible
 
⸻
 
DNS Services
Validate:
	•	DNS service operational
	•	Forward lookup zones operational
	•	Reverse lookup zones operational
 
⸻
 
Replication Status
Validate:
	•	Active Directory replication healthy
	•	No replication failures
	•	No lingering replication errors
 
⸻
 
Domain Controller Discovery Validation
Execute from a DR Domain Controller or DR Management Server.
nltest /dclist:corp.company.com
Expected Result:
List of Domain Controllers Returned
 
⸻
 
Domain Controller Locator Validation
nltest /dsgetdc:corp.company.com
Expected Result:
DC Found
 
⸻
 
DNS Validation
nslookup corp.company.com
Expected Result:
Successful Name Resolution
 
⸻
 
Kerberos Validation
Test-NetConnection <DC-IP> -Port 88
Expected Result:
TcpTestSucceeded : True
 
⸻
 
LDAP Validation
Test-NetConnection <DC-IP> -Port 389
Expected Result:
TcpTestSucceeded : True
 
⸻
 
SMB Validation
Test-NetConnection <DC-IP> -Port 445
Expected Result:
TcpTestSucceeded : True
 
⸻
 
Evidence Required
Capture:
	•	Domain Controller list
	•	Domain Controller locator output
	•	DNS validation output
	•	Port validation output
	•	Validation timestamp
 
⸻
 
Success Criteria
Domain Controllers are:
	•	Online
	•	Discoverable
	•	Responding to DNS
	•	Responding to LDAP
	•	Responding to Kerberos
	•	Responding to SMB
 
⸻
 
Go / No-Go Decision
Proceed only if all Domain Controller validations pass.
If any validation fails:
NO-GO
Stop recovery activities and engage the Active Directory team.
 
⸻
 
16. DNS Validation and Health Verification
Objective
Validate DNS services required to support recovered workloads.
DNS is one of the most common causes of recovery failures.
Many domain join, FSx, application, and authentication failures are ultimately DNS-related.
 
⸻
 
Background
Recovered systems depend heavily upon DNS to locate:
	•	Domain Controllers
	•	FSx File Systems
	•	Databases
	•	Application Endpoints
	•	Load Balancers
Failure to validate DNS before workload recovery often results in prolonged troubleshooting.
 
⸻
 
Dependencies
Requires:
	•	Domain Controllers validated
	•	DNS service operational
 
⸻
 
Validate Domain Resolution
nslookup corp.company.com
Expected Result:
Successful Resolution
 
⸻
 
Validate Domain Controller Records
nslookup _ldap._tcp.dc._msdcs.corp.company.com
Expected Result:
SRV Records Returned
 
⸻
 
Validate Reverse Resolution
nslookup <DC-IP>
Expected Result:
Hostname Returned
 
⸻
 
Validate DNS Port Connectivity
Test-NetConnection <DC-IP> -Port 53
Expected Result:
TcpTestSucceeded : True
 
⸻
 
Validate DNS Configuration
Windows:
ipconfig /all
Linux:
cat /etc/resolv.conf
Confirm:
	•	Correct DNS Servers
	•	Correct Search Suffix
	•	Correct Domain
 
⸻
 
Evidence Required
Capture:
	•	nslookup output
	•	SRV record lookup
	•	Port validation output
	•	DNS configuration
 
⸻
 
Success Criteria
DNS successfully resolves:
	•	Domain Controllers
	•	Active Directory records
	•	Internal infrastructure
 
⸻
 
Common Failures
Domain Resolution Failure
Potential Causes:
	•	DNS service failure
	•	Incorrect DNS configuration
	•	Security Group restrictions
 
⸻
 
SRV Record Failure
Potential Causes:
	•	Active Directory registration failure
	•	DNS replication failure
 
⸻
 
Go / No-Go Decision
Proceed only if DNS validation succeeds.
Otherwise:
NO-GO
 
⸻
 
17. FSx Recovery and Validation
Objective
Validate that Amazon FSx for Windows File Server is available and capable of supporting recovered workloads.
FSx frequently represents one of the most critical dependencies in the environment.
Application recovery should not proceed until FSx functionality has been validated.
 
⸻
 
Background
Applications often rely on FSx for:
	•	Shared storage
	•	Configuration files
	•	Application binaries
	•	User data
	•	Service account access
	•	SMB file shares
A healthy EC2 server does not guarantee application functionality if FSx remains unavailable.
 
⸻
 
Dependencies
Before validating FSx:
	•	Domain Controllers validated
	•	DNS validated
	•	Network validation completed
 
⸻
 
Validate File System Availability
Navigate:
FSx
→ File Systems
Confirm:
Status = Available
 
⸻
 
Validate DNS Alias Resolution
nslookup <fsx-alias>
Expected Result:
Alias Resolved
 
⸻
 
Validate DNS Reachability
Important:
Previous recovery exercises identified DNS reachability issues as a cause of FSx recovery failures.
Validate:
Test-NetConnection <DNS-IP> -Port 53
Expected Result:
TcpTestSucceeded : True
 
⸻
 
Validate SMB Connectivity
Test-NetConnection <fsx-name> -Port 445
Expected Result:
TcpTestSucceeded : True
 
⸻
 
Validate Share Access
dir \\fsx-name\share
Expected Result:
Contents Returned
 
⸻
 
Validate Authentication
Confirm:
	•	Service accounts authenticate
	•	Access permissions function
	•	Required shares accessible
 
⸻
 
Validate Access from DR WorkSpace
Using a DR WorkSpace:
\\fsx-name\share
Expected Result:
Accessible
 
⸻
 
Evidence Required
Capture:
	•	FSx status
	•	DNS alias validation
	•	Port validation
	•	Share access validation
	•	DR WorkSpace validation
 
⸻
 
Common Failures
DNS Unreachable
Symptoms:
FSx Recovery Failure
Potential Causes:
	•	Incorrect DNS configuration
	•	Domain Controller unavailable
	•	Security Group restrictions
 
⸻
 
SMB Connectivity Failure
Symptoms:
Access Denied
or
Unable to Connect
Potential Causes:
	•	Port 445 blocked
	•	Security Group restrictions
	•	Network ACL restrictions
 
⸻
 
Authentication Failure
Potential Causes:
	•	Domain Controller unavailable
	•	Trust relationship failure
	•	Service account issues
 
⸻
 
Success Criteria
FSx is considered operational when:
	•	File System Available
	•	DNS Alias Resolves
	•	Port 445 Reachable
	•	Shares Accessible
	•	Authentication Successful
	•	Access Validated from DR WorkSpace
 
⸻
 
Go / No-Go Decision
Proceed only if FSx validation succeeds.
If any critical FSx validation fails:
NO-GO
Stop application recovery and engage:
	•	Storage Team
	•	Active Directory Team
	•	Infrastructure Team
as appropriate.
 
⸻
 
Part 2 Summary
The Disaster Recovery environment is considered ready for database and application recovery only when:
	•	Domain Controllers validated
	•	DNS validated
	•	FSx validated
Failure of any component requires remediation before proceeding.
Proceed to:
Part 3 – Database Recovery Foundations, Application Recovery, Web Recovery, and Network Validation
 
