18. Database Recovery Foundations
Objective
Recover and validate database infrastructure required to support application services within the Disaster Recovery environment.
Databases frequently represent one of the most critical dependencies within the recovery chain. Application services should not be validated until database recovery has been completed successfully.
This section focuses on foundational database recovery validation. Detailed SQL Server Always On Availability Group (AOAG) recovery procedures will be covered in a dedicated section later in this document.
 
⸻
 
Background
Many applications can start successfully even when database connectivity is unavailable.
This creates a false indication that recovery has succeeded.
Examples include:
	•	Login failures
	•	Missing application data
	•	Transaction failures
	•	Report failures
	•	API failures
	•	Service initialization failures
Database validation must therefore be performed before application validation begins.
 
⸻
 
Dependencies
Before database recovery begins:
	•	Domain Controllers validated
	•	DNS validated
	•	FSx validated
	•	Required subnets available
	•	Security groups validated
 
⸻
 
Recovery Methods
Approved recovery methods may include:
AWS Elastic Disaster Recovery (DRS)
Used when database servers are protected through continuous replication.
AWS Backup
Used when backup and restore operations are required.
AMI-Based Recovery
Used for approved disaster recovery scenarios where AMI restoration is the designated recovery method.
 
⸻
 
Initial Recovery Validation
Navigate:
EC2
→ Instances
Confirm:
Instance State = Running
Validate:
System Status Check = Passed
Instance Status Check = Passed
 
⸻
 
Network Validation
Validate database listener ports.
Examples:
Test-NetConnection <db-server> -Port 1433
Expected:
TcpTestSucceeded : True
 
⸻
 
DNS Validation
Validate hostname resolution.
nslookup <database-server>
Expected:
Correct DR IP Returned
 
⸻
 
Service Validation
Windows:
Get-Service
Verify:
SQL Server Service = Running
Linux:
systemctl status <database-service>
Expected:
Active (Running)
 
⸻
 
Authentication Validation
Validate:
	•	Service accounts
	•	Database service accounts
	•	Integrated authentication
	•	Application connectivity accounts
 
⸻
 
Evidence Required
Capture:
	•	Recovery method
	•	Recovery timestamps
	•	Instance health checks
	•	Database service status
	•	Port validation
	•	DNS validation
 
⸻
 
Success Criteria
Database infrastructure is considered operational when:
	•	Instance running
	•	Health checks passed
	•	Database service running
	•	DNS functional
	•	Required ports reachable
 
⸻
 
Go / No-Go Decision
Proceed only if database recovery succeeds.
If validation fails:
NO-GO
Recovery activities stop until database services are restored.
 
⸻
 
