21. Network Validation
Objective
Validate network connectivity between recovered infrastructure components.
Many recovery failures are caused by network misconfiguration rather than server failures.
 
⸻
 
Background
Common network-related issues include:
	•	Security Group mismatches
	•	Route Table errors
	•	CIDR translation issues
	•	Network ACL restrictions
	•	DNS failures
 
⸻
 
Dependencies
Network validation occurs after server recovery and before domain integration validation.
 
⸻
 
Security Group Validation
Validate Security Groups permit communication between:
	•	Domain Controllers
	•	FSx
	•	Databases
	•	Application Servers
	•	Web Servers
	•	WorkSpaces
 
⸻
 
DR CIDR Translation Validation
Important:
Production and Disaster Recovery environments may use different CIDR ranges.
Validate:
Production Source
        ↓
DR Translation
        ↓
Security Group Rule
Confirm that security group sources reference the correct DR networks.
 
⸻
 
Route Table Validation
Navigate:
VPC
→ Route Tables
Validate routes for:
	•	Domain Controllers
	•	FSx
	•	Databases
	•	Application Servers
	•	WorkSpaces
 
⸻
 
DNS Configuration Validation
Windows:
ipconfig /all
Linux:
cat /etc/resolv.conf
Confirm:
	•	DNS servers correct
	•	Search suffix correct
	•	Domain configuration correct
 
⸻
 
Connectivity Validation
Validate connectivity between recovered servers and dependencies.
Examples:
Test-NetConnection <server> -Port 443
Test-NetConnection <server> -Port 1433
Test-NetConnection <server> -Port 445
Expected:
TcpTestSucceeded : True
 
⸻
 
Evidence Required
Capture:
	•	Security Group validation
	•	Route Table validation
	•	DNS validation
	•	Connectivity validation
 
⸻
 
Success Criteria
Recovered systems communicate successfully across all required network paths.
 
⸻
 
Common Failures
Security Group Mismatch
Symptoms:
Connection Timeout
Potential Causes:
	•	Missing rule
	•	Incorrect source CIDR
